track_notes: Some off-trail scrambling required to reach the peak
Need to bushwhack down from summit to trail for a short distance.  Then you are on the Arizona Trail.
track_title: Oracle Ridge Summit back to trailhead

track_notes: From the General Hitchcock Hwy just before the Summerhaven turnoff, turn right on Control Rd and park at the signed Oracle Ridge Trail Head at about 7800 ft elevation. One way distance to the summit is 3.3 miles with gross elevation gain of 2,456 ft and an average slope of 26 degrees. After the first 0.5 mile with little elevation change from the trailhead, the trail descends about 900 feet in elevation over the next 1.8 miles to Dan Saddle. From there it is 1.0 mile and nearly 800 ft of ascent to the summit. The last 0.3 mile to the summit is off-trail bushwhack and possibly the steepest part of the hike. There is a lot of scrub at the summit so a mast might be a good addition to your gear.

This is almost the same as previous routes, except that I acquired the ridgeline a little sooner, going up to the saddle between the summit and the previous hilltop.  Although the trail can take you a little bit higher before starting a bushwhack, I thought this route had a shorter steep section.  Once you reach the saddle, it is a milder climb.  Also the Bighorn Fire of 2020 cleared much of the brush, and a new fenceline was installed and it appears that they did some clearing while putting that in.  This is still a longish hike and the downhill first couple of miles followed by a climb throw you off compared to the usual uphill-only hikes to the summit.  The trek back can feel longer as it does a lot of climb.  Most of the trees in the area have burned so it is a very exposed hike.  There were still a few charred tree remains on the trail when I went in July 2021 but most of the trail has been cleared.
track_title: Oracle Ridge After the Bighorn Fire
